Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Emergence is a fascinating topic.
 It has the ability to literally make or break a large system of systems.
 Emergence can be a good thing or a bad thing, a predictable or unpredictable
 thing (depending on the definition you ascribe to), and most definitely
 due to the interactions between system components.
 The key to emergent behavior is most definitely the communication between
 various system nodes.
 The influence that they can exert on each other and have cascade through
 the system lead to emergent behaviors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Since communication is the key factor in emergence, the easiest place to
 observe emergent behaviors is in modern day social networks.
 Networks like Facebook and Twitter have evolved substantially from the
 day that they went lives many years ago.
 The networks themselves have been largely manipulated due to the users
 of the systems themselves.
 The two systems mentioned, in particular, have largely benefited from this
 emergent behaviors.
 They have gained more users, more advertisers, and thus, more profits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Emergence doesn't come without its set of difficulties though.
 Even using an optimistic definition of the topic still leaves some aspect
 of mystery.
 The pessimistic definition leaves little hope to attempt to engineer emergence
 into any system.
 It even leaves little hope in trying to predict it.
 Until these ultra-large scale systems are more thoroughly analyzed and
 understood, emergent behaviors present in them will remain a bit mysterious.
 Finally, since these systems are ever-growing and every-changing, doing
 any sort of long term analysis seems futile.
 The better route may be trying to analyze the human participants within
 the system since their individual philosophies also play a large part in
 the emergence that will manifest in the system.
\end_layout

